\section{Item quality}{

Parameters were sampled from uniform distributions on ranges that
reflect four levels of item quality, defined by the probability of a
correct response for non-masters (\eqn{P_0}) and masters (\eqn{P_1}):\tabular{llll}{
   Code \tab Label \tab \eqn{P_0} range \tab \eqn{P_1} range \cr
   \code{HDLV} \tab High Discrimination, Low Variability \tab \eqn{[0.05, 0.15]} \tab \eqn{[0.85, 0.95]} \cr
   \code{HDHV} \tab High Discrimination, High Variability \tab \eqn{[0.00, 0.20]} \tab \eqn{[0.80, 0.999]} \cr
   \code{LDLV} \tab Low Discrimination, Low Variability \tab \eqn{[0.15, 0.25]} \tab \eqn{[0.75, 0.85]} \cr
   \code{LDHV} \tab Low Discrimination, High Variability \tab \eqn{[0.10, 0.30]} \tab \eqn{[0.70, 0.90]} \cr
}


For \strong{DINA/DINO}: \code{slip = 1 - P1} and \code{guess = P0}, independently
sampled per item and clipped to \eqn{[0.001, 0.999]}.

For \strong{GDINA}: \eqn{P_{min} \sim P_0} and \eqn{P_{max} \sim P_1}
are independently sampled per item; the probability of a correct
response increases linearly with the count of mastered required
attributes: \eqn{P_{min} + (m / K_j) \times (P_{max} - P_{min})},
where \eqn{m} is the number of required attributes mastered.
